Multiple datasets were loaded from a single Excel file, with each sheet representing a logical table (Customer, Product, Sales).

customer = pd.read_excel ("store data1.xlsx")
product = pd.read_excel ("store data1.xlsx", sheet_name= 1)
sales = pd.read_excel ("store data1.xlsx", sheet_name= 2)

Retail data is often delivered in Excel format with multiple sheets.
Loading each sheet separately preserves table structure and supports proper data modeling.

Checked for missing (null) values column-wise across all datasets.

customer.isna().sum()
product.isna().sum()
sales.isna().sum()

Identified duplicate rows in each dataset
Duplicate records can inflate: sales totals,profit calculations,customer counts
Detecting duplicates ensures transactional accuracy.

customer.duplicated().sum()
product.duplicated().sum()
sales.duplicated().sum()

Removed duplicate records from all tables.

customer = customer.drop_duplicates()
product = product.drop_duplicates()
sales = sales.drop_duplicates()

Converted numeric fields to proper numeric data types, coercing invalid values to null.

full_data["profit"] = pd.to_numeric(full_data["profit"], errors="coerce")
full_data = full_data.apply(pd.to_numeric, errors="coerce")

Converted order and ship dates to datetime format.
Datetime format is required for: time-based analysis, trend analysis

full_data["order_date"] = pd.to_datetime(full_data["order_date"])
full_data["ship_date"] = pd.to_datetime(full_data["ship_date"])

Standardized column names by converting them to lowercase and replacing spaces with underscores.

full_data.columns =full_data.columns.str.lower().str.replace(" ","_")

Formatted numeric output to display two decimal places

pd.options.display.float_format='{:,.2F}'.format
